Stock Market Analysis of Various Companies Using Python¶

Business Scenario: Data Science extracts meaningful insight from chunks of raw data, which is useful to different business segments for planning their future course of action. Finance is probably one of the first to catch on to this trend with a rise in the penetration of analytics into many aspects of our lives. Here, we will analyze data from the stock market for some technology stocks such as Apple, Google, Amazon, and Microsoft.

Goal: I'm going to extract and analyze the information, visualize it, and look at different ways to analyze the risk of a stock, based on its performance history using Python libraries such as Pandas, Seaborn, and Matplotlib.

About the Data: The stocks chosen for analysis:

  • Apple
  • Google
  • Microsoft
  • Amazon

For the start, we shall investigate the Amazon stock individually and then move on to the combined analysis.

Source used for the stocks data: https://in.finance.yahoo.com/

My work consists of the following tasks:

  • Reading the Data from Yahoo finance website directly.
  • Performing cleaning.
  • Studying the change in stock price over time
  • Visualizing the change in a stock’s volume being traded, over time
  • Moving average of various stocks
  • Daily return average of a stock
  • Checking the Trend based on Daily Return.
  • Visualizing trend frequency through a Pie Chart.
  • Studying correlation between the daily returns of different stocks

Daily Return Average of a stock¶

In [37]:
colors = ['blue', 'orange', 'green', 'red']

# Calculate daily returns for each stock
for stock in data:
    stocks_df[f'{stock}_Daily_Return'] = stocks_df['Close'][stock].pct_change()

# Create subplots
fig, axs = plt.subplots(len(data), 1, figsize=(10, 4* len(data)))

# Plot daily returns for each stock in a separate subplot
for i, (stock, color) in enumerate(zip(data, colors)):
    axs[i].plot(stocks_df.index, stocks_df[f'{stock}_Daily_Return'], label=f'{stock} Daily Return', color=color)
    axs[i].set_title(f'{stock} Daily Return Over Time', color=color, fontweight='bold')
    axs[i].set_xlabel('Date')
    axs[i].set_ylabel('Daily Return')
    axs[i].legend()
    axs[i].grid(True)

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# Print maximum daily return for each stock

daily_returns = stocks_df[[f'{stock}_Daily_Return' for stock in data]]
correlation_matrix = daily_returns.corr()

plt.figure(figsize=(8, 8))
heatmap = sns.heatmap(correlation_matrix, annot=True, cmap='coolwarm', linewidths=.5)

# Add a label to the colorbar
cbar = heatmap.collections[0].colorbar
cbar.set_label('Correlation Coefficient', rotation=270, labelpad=15)

plt.title('Correlation Between Daily Returns of Stocks')
plt.xlabel(' ')
plt.ylabel(' ')
plt.show()
